\begin{document}
\section{Introduction}
\subsection{Background}
\section{Experimental Methods}
\subsection{Materials}
\subsection{Procedure}
\section{Results}
\subsection{Data Analysis}
\section{Discussion}
\subsection{Limitations}
\subsection{Conclusion}
\end{document}
```

Next, we'll use the `tocstyle` package to customize the appearance of our table of contents. We'll also use the `tocbibind` package to automatically include the bibliography in the table of contents (if we have one). Here's the relevant commands:

```
\usepackage{tocstyle}
\usepackage{tocbibind}
```

Finally, we can generate the table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command. This will automatically create a list of all the sections and subsections in our document, and include them in the table of contents. Here's the complete document with all the necessary commands:

```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocstyle}
\usepackage{tocbibind}
\begin{document}
\section{Introduction}
\subsection{Background}
\section{Experimental Methods}
\subsection{Materials}
\subsection{Procedure}
\section{Results}
\subsection{Data Analysis}
\section{Discussion}
\subsection{Limitations}
\subsection{Conclusion}
\tableofcontents
\end{document}
```

When we compile this document, we'll get a table of contents that looks something like this:

```
Table of Contents
-----------------
1. Introduction
  1.1. Background
2. Experimental Methods
  2.1. Materials
  2.2. Procedure
3. Results
  3.1. Data Analysis
4. Discussion
  4.1. Limitations
  4.2. Conclusion
```

As you can see, the table of contents includes all the headings in our document, and organizes them in a logical order based on their hierarchy.

